{"parentUuid":"f2606886-105e-4f16-a29f-171a9df01a01","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011Ccrw7QUjYVUGEuJUKYRSu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018cYqNA6x5kjtTye7x9WNGD","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5466,"cache_creation_input_tokens":18400,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":216,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":18400},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":5466,"output_tokens":216,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":18400,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":18400,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccrw7PbeciXNfPqnBeu6x","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"718b1d71-9db8-4896-98bb-16b1b4a8d378","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:10:46.521Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"718b1d71-9db8-4896-98bb-16b1b4a8d378","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018cYqNA6x5kjtTye7x9WNGD","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tfeature: usage CSV export (GET /v1/usage/export)\n3\tbrief: PROJECT.md + .pipeline/requirements.md (authoritative)\n4\trun_type: revised (single allowed pass; addressed .pipeline/plan-audit.md material flags — see ## Revision notes)\n5\trepomix_pack_sha256: 67eadd304a8283772e6bc7833c535e9f4e6dfc088dcde667aac265fc0083de68\n6\trepomix_pack_files: 54\n7\trepomix_pack_tokens: 26820\n8\tdesign_source: none (CSV API, no UI)\n9\tmigration_added: false\n10\tinfra_change: false\n11\tnew_stored_data: false\n12\ttest_strategy: pyramid\n13\ttasks_file_emitted: false  # decomposition trigger under the CURRENT engine contract is the SINGLE >=25-estimated-files leg; the old >=15-criteria OR-leg was RETIRED. Estimated change set ~14 files is below 25, so no tasks.md. Criteria count (22) is not a decomposition trigger under the current contract.\n14\t---\n15\t\n16\t# Plan — usage CSV export (`GET /v1/usage/export`)\n17\t\n18\t## Summary\n19\t\n20\tWe add one read-only endpoint, `GET /v1/usage/export`, that streams the authenticated\n21\tcaller's own `usage_rollup` rows as an RFC 4180 CSV (`customer_id,metric,window_start,\n22\ttotal_quantity`), with optional `customer_id` / `metric` / `from` / `to` filters, a hard\n23\t100,000-row cap, and OWASP CSV-formula-injection escaping at the encoding boundary. The\n24\tcore approach is a **streaming response backed by a PostgreSQL server-side cursor inside a\n25\ttenant-scoped transaction**, chosen over buffering the whole result in memory because a\n26\t100k-row export buffered per concurrent request is a cheap memory-exhaustion (DoS) vector,\n27\tand over pagination because the brief scoped size control to \"row cap + filters, no\n28\tpagination this slice.\" The feature reuses every existing edge control (API-key auth,\n29\tTier-2 per-key throttle, security headers, error envelope, structured logging, RLS\n30\tbackstop) and reuses the exact validated identifier types the ingest/query paths already\n31\tenforce — so it adds a new HTTP surface without a new auth mechanism, a new migration, or\n32\tany change to the existing endpoints. It is intentionally isolated in new modules so the\n33\texisting `GET /v1/usage` code path is untouched (the brief's no-behavior-change constraint).\n34\t\n35\tThe authoritative brief (`.pipeline/requirements.md`) resolved nearly everything; its one\n36\t`Open` item (the documented p95 target number) is carried below as Open Question 1 with a\n37\tstated default (p95 < 500 ms at the cap). Everything in the brief's `Out of scope` list\n38\t(pagination, admin-only gating, other formats/compression/async jobs, changes to existing\n39\tendpoints, extra audit logging) is treated as a hard exclusion and not planned.\n40\t\n41\t## Stack notes\n42\t\n43\tThe feature sits entirely inside Meterly's existing stack; every default was assessed and\n44\tkept — none swapped.\n45\t\n46\t- **Backend — Python 3.12 / FastAPI (kept).** The endpoint is one more FastAPI route on the\n47\t  existing app; mirrors the proven `GET /v1/usage` composition. No reason to deviate.\n48\t- **CSV encoding — Python stdlib `csv` (kept, and mandated by the brief).** *What:* use\n49\t  `csv.writer` with an explicit RFC 4180 dialect. *Why over a hand-rolled encoder:* a\n50\t  hand-rolled encoder is the classic source of quoting bugs (a value containing a comma,\n51\t  quote, or embedded newline breaks a naive `\",\".join(...)`), and getting RFC 4180 quoting\n52\t  exactly right is precisely what stdlib `csv` already does and is tested to do. *How:*\n53\t  `csv.writer` with `lineterminator=\"\\r\\n\"` (RFC 4180 CRLF) and `QUOTE_MINIMAL` (quote only\n54\t  fields containing comma/quote/CR/LF) writing into a per-row `io.StringIO` we drain and\n55\t  reset each row — this reuses stdlib correctness while keeping constant memory (we never\n56\t  hold more than one row's text). Formula-injection escaping is applied to text cells\n57\t  *before* they reach the writer (see the CSV-encoding section).\n58\t- **Data store — PostgreSQL (kept), read-only, no migration.** The export reads the\n59\t  existing `usage_rollup` aggregate. No new table, column, index, or data-classification\n60\t  surface — consistent with the brief's \"no new stored data.\" See Data section for the\n61\t  ordering/index tradeoff this creates and why we still add no migration.\n62\t- **Streaming — Starlette `StreamingResponse` + SQLAlchemy async `session.stream()` (new\n63\t  use of an existing capability).** Assessed against buffering and against chunked keyset\n64\t  pagination; the server-side-cursor-in-one-transaction option won on simplicity +\n65\t  single-snapshot consistency. Full rationale in the Backend section.\n66\t- **Auth — existing API-key facade (kept).** Any authenticated key may export its own\n67\t  tenant's data (brief: not admin-gated). Reuses `require_api_key` + the Tier-2 per-key\n68\t  throttle exactly as `GET /v1/usage` does.\n69\t- **Observability / logging — structlog facade + CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry (kept).** One new\n70\t  `usage.export` audit event through the existing `get_logger()` facade; no new SLO or\n71\t  burn-rate alarm for this reporting slice (the binding perf criterion is a documented p95\n72\t  sanity check, not an SLO — see Open Question 1).\n73\t- **Infra / IaC — no change.** No provisioned resource is added; the route ships through the\n74\t  existing CI → build-provenance → `deploy.yml` chain with no `infra/` edit. (The `infra/`\n75\t  files marked modified in the working tree belong to earlier work on this branch, not this\n76\t  feature.)\n77\t\n78\tNo default is being recommended against; nothing here needs a checkpoint override on stack\n79\tgrounds.\n80\t\n81\t## Backend — route, service, repository\n82\t\n83\t### Route — `src/api/routes/usage_export.py` (new module)\n84\t\n85\t*What:* a new router module exposing `GET /v1/usage/export`, registered in `src/main.py`.\n86\t*Why a new module rather than adding to `src/api/routes/usage.py`:* the brief requires \"no\n87\tbehavior change to any existing endpoint\"; putting the export in its own module keeps\n88\t`usage.py` (which owns `GET /v1/usage`) literally untouched, making the no-change guarantee\n89\ttrivially auditable in the diff, and matches the existing per-resource module convention\n90\t(`events.py`, `usage.py`, `quotas.py`). *How:* it reuses the same sibling dependency the\n91\tother routes use to pin ordering —\n92\t\n93\t- `_require_authenticated_and_throttled` (auth `require_api_key` → Tier-2 per-key throttle,\n94\t  in that order) — copied as a sibling, not imported, per the established convention that\n95\t  each route's dependency chain stays independently readable. No admin-scope gate (any\n96\t  authenticated key may export — brief resolved).\n97\t\n98\tThe handler is deliberately two-phase to make the row cap a clean pre-body 422:\n99\t\n100\t1. **Pre-flight cap check (still a normal request, can 422 cleanly).** Call the service's\n101\t   `prepare_export(principal, params)`, which runs a `COUNT(*)` with the same filters inside\n102\t   a tenant-scoped transaction and raises `HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=...)` if the\n103\t   count exceeds 100,000. 422 already maps to `validation_failed` in `src/api/errors.py`'s\n104\t   `_STATUS_TO_CODE`, so this needs no `AppError` — a plain `HTTPException(422)` yields the\n105\t   brief-required `{\"error\":{\"code\":\"validation_failed\",...}}` envelope. *Why a pre-flight\n106\t   count and not \"stream until the 100,001st row\":* once we return a `StreamingResponse` the\n107\t   status line is already `200` and the first bytes may be on the wire — we cannot retro-send\n108\t   a 422. The cap decision must therefore precede any response body. The count is an\n109\t   index-prefix scan over the caller's `api_key_id` and is cheap.\n110\t   *Fail-closed on a non-cap error (AC22):* any **unexpected** error raised during this\n111\t   pre-flight `COUNT` phase — a DB connection drop, a query error — is deliberately **not**\n112\t   caught and **not** a 422. It propagates uncaught to the catch-all\n113\t   `@app.exception_handler(Exception)` boundary in `src/api/errors.py`, which returns the\n114\t   generic `500` envelope (`{\"error\":{\"code\":\"internal\",\"message\":\"an internal error\n115\t   occurred\",\"requestId\":...}}` — no stack, SQL, or internal path leaked, ASVS 16.5.x), with\n116\t   the pre-flight transaction rolled back and **no `StreamingResponse` ever constructed**, so\n117\t   no partial body is emitted. This phase is *cleanly recoverable* precisely because it runs\n118\t   before any response byte — it is the failure path AC22 exercises, distinct from R3's\n119\t   post-200 mid-stream case where the envelope can no longer apply.\n120\t2. **Stream.** Return `StreamingResponse(stream_export_csv(principal, params),\n121\t   media_type=\"text/csv; charset=utf-8\", headers={\"Content-Disposition\": 'attachment;\n122\t   filename=\"usage-export-<UTC>.csv\"'})`. The generator is consumed by Starlette *after* the\n123\t   handler returns, so it opens its **own** tenant-scoped transaction (see below).\n124\t\n125\tThe route also declares explicit OpenAPI `responses=` metadata (`200 -> text/csv`, `422 ->\n126\tvalidation_failed` envelope) so the served schema describes the streamed route accurately\n127\t(a `StreamingResponse` has no auto `response_model`) — this is what makes DAST-1 true.\n128\t\n129\tQuery-param binding mirrors `GET /v1/usage`: `params: Annotated[UsageExportQueryParams,\n130\tQuery()]`.\n131\t\n132\t### Query schema — `src/api/schemas/usage_export.py` (new file)\n133\t\n134\t*What:* `UsageExportQueryParams(BaseModel)` with `extra=\"forbid\"`, all fields optional:\n135\t- `customer_id: CustomerId | None = None` and `metric: Metric | None = None` — **reusing the\n136\t  exact `constr` allowlists** from `src/api/schemas/events.py` (`^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$` /\n137\t  `{1,64}$`). *Why reuse rather than re-declare loosely:* these are the same identifiers over\n138\t  the same SQL sink, so the validation contract must be identical to the ingest/query path;\n139\t  importing the shared `constr` types keeps the anchored-allowlist charset in one place.\n140\t- `from_: AwareDatetime | None = Field(default=None, alias=\"from\")` and\n141\t  `to: AwareDatetime | None = None`, with `populate_by_name=True`. *Why the alias:* `from` is\n142\t  a Python keyword, so the field is `from_` bound to the `from` query name. `AwareDatetime`\n143\t  rejects naive datetimes (the existing idiom — a naive value would silently mis-attribute a\n144\t  window), and a `model_validator` enforces `from <= to` and both within `[now-90d, now+1h]`,\n145\t  reusing the same `_MAX_WINDOW_LOOKBACK` / `_MAX_WINDOW_LOOKAHEAD` bounds `usage.py` uses.\n146\t- `extra=\"forbid\"` so an unknown query param (typo, probe, or a client-supplied `api_key_id`)\n147\t  is rejected 422 rather than silently ignored — the same mass-assignment posture the write\n148\t  schemas use, applied to a read.\n149\t\n150\tA new file (not an edit to `usage.py`'s schema) keeps the existing `UsageQueryParams`\n151\tuntouched.\n152\t\n153\t### Service — `src/services/usage_export_service.py` (new)\n154\t\n155\tTwo public coroutines plus two module constants:\n156\t\n157\t- `MAX_EXPORT_ROWS = 100_000`, `EXPORT_COLUMNS = (\"customer_id\",\"metric\",\"window_start\",\n158\t  \"total_quantity\")`.\n159\t- `async def prepare_export(principal, params) -> None` — opens `scoped_transaction(\n160\t  principal.api_key_id)`, calls `count_usage_rollups(...)`, raises `HTTPException(422,\n161\t  \"result exceeds 100000 rows; narrow with customer_id, metric, from, and/or to\")` when over\n162\t  cap; logs the rejection at `warn` (`usage.export.rejected`, `reason=\"row_cap_exceeded\"`).\n163\t  Any **other** (non-cap) exception it raises — e.g. a DB error from the `COUNT` — is left to\n164\t  propagate to the error-envelope boundary (`500 internal`, fail-closed, transaction rolled\n165\t  back, before any response byte); it is deliberately **not** swallowed or masked as a 200\n166\t  (AC22 verifies this safe-error shape and that no stream is started).\n167\t- `async def stream_export_csv(principal, params) -> AsyncIterator[bytes]` — the body\n168\t  generator. *This is the load-bearing streaming design:*\n169\t  - It opens its **own** `scoped_transaction(principal.api_key_id)` and does all DB work\n170\t    inside it. *Why inside the generator, not the handler:* Starlette pulls the generator\n171\t    after the handler returns, so a transaction opened in the handler would already be closed\n172\t    when the first row is read. Opening it in the generator keeps two invariants alive for the\n173\t    whole stream: (a) the `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id` that arms the RLS backstop is in\n174\t    force for every streamed read, and (b) the server-side cursor stays valid.\n175\t  - It yields the **header row first, always** (so an empty result is a 200 header-only CSV,\n176\t    never a 404 — mirrors the existing zeros-not-404 contract), then `async for record in\n177\t    stream_usage_rollups(..., limit=MAX_EXPORT_ROWS)` yields one CSV-encoded row at a time.\n178\t  - Constant memory: each row is encoded into a reused `io.StringIO`, `.getvalue()` is\n179\t    yielded as UTF-8 bytes, then the buffer is truncated — we never hold more than one row's\n180\t    text, and `session.stream()` fetches from the DB via a server-side cursor rather than\n181\t    buffering the whole result client-side.\n182\t  - In a `finally`, it emits exactly one `usage.export` audit log (row count, `capped`,\n183\t    `completed`) — placed in `finally` so a client disconnect mid-stream still records what\n184\t    was sent. Structlog contextvars (`requestId`/`traceId`) are still bound here because the\n185\t    body iteration runs in the same request task.\n186\t\n187\t*Why a single server-side-cursor transaction rather than chunked keyset pagination:* the\n188\tbrief scoped this to \"streaming response, rows written as read.\" A single transaction gives\n189\tone consistent snapshot and simple, correct code. The cost is a real operability tradeoff:\n190\tthe DB transaction/connection is held open for the duration of the (possibly slow) client\n191\tdownload, so a slow reader can pin a pooled connection. That blast radius is bounded three\n192\tways — the 100k row cap + `LIMIT 100000` bounds the stream, the Tier-2 per-key throttle\n193\tbounds how many exports one key starts, and the connection pool is sized for it. If\n194\tconnection-hold ever proves problematic under load, the follow-up is batched keyset\n195\tpagination (short transaction per batch) — noted, not built this slice (accepted risk R1).\n196\t\n197\t*Streaming-through-middleware caveat:* the app's edge middleware are `BaseHTTPMiddleware`\n198\tsubclasses (security headers, body-size, Tier-1, request-context logging). Modern Starlette\n199\tstreams a `StreamingResponse` through `BaseHTTPMiddleware` without buffering the whole body,\n200\tso constant memory holds and the request-context completion log fires when the stream\n201\tfinishes (its `duration` correctly spans the full export). This is load-bearing for the\n202\tconstant-memory requirement, so an integration test asserts the body is streamed (first\n203\tbytes observable before the generator is exhausted / memory stays bounded on a large\n204\texport) rather than assuming it.\n205\t\n206\t### Repository — `src/repositories/usage_repo.py` (extend, existing `find_usage_rollup`\n207\tuntouched)\n208\t\n209\tAdd two functions and a minimal export projection dataclass:\n210\t\n211\t- `@dataclass(frozen=True) class UsageRollupExportRecord: customer_id; metric; window_start;\n212\t  total_quantity` — **only the four exported columns** (no `event_count`, `updated_at`, or\n213\t  `api_key_id`): the minimal-projection rule (ASVS 14.x / the existing \"never a raw ORM row\"\n214\t  convention).\n215\t- `async def count_usage_rollups(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id=None, metric=None,\n216\t  window_from=None, window_to=None) -> int` — `SELECT count(*) ... WHERE api_key_id=:k`\n217\t  plus optional `AND customer_id=:c`, `AND metric=:m`, `AND window_start >= :from`,\n218\t  `AND window_start <= :to`. Backs the pre-flight cap check.\n219\t- `async def stream_usage_rollups(session, *, api_key_id, ..., limit) -> AsyncIterator[\n220\t  UsageRollupExportRecord]` — same WHERE, plus `ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric\n221\t  ASC` and `LIMIT :limit`, executed with `await session.stream(text(...), params)` and\n222\t  `async for row in result.mappings(): yield UsageRollupExportRecord(...)`.\n223\t\n224\tEvery query is **scoped by the authenticated `api_key_id` first** (the row-level-security\n225\tinvariant), with all user values passed as bound parameters (`text(...)` + params dict — no\n226\tstring concatenation). The `ORDER BY` clause is a **fixed literal** built from server-side\n227\tcolumn names, never from client input, so the sort key is not a tampering sink. This is the\n228\tprimary tenant-isolation control (see the Data and Auth sections for the RLS-backstop\n229\tcaveat).\n230\t\n231\t## CSV encoding & formula-injection escaping — `src/api/csv_export.py` (new facade)\n232\t\n233\t*What:* the single boundary that owns the CSV column contract and the OWASP formula-injection\n234\tescape. *Why a facade module:* centralizing the escape (rather than inlining it in the\n235\tgenerator) makes it greppable, independently unit-testable, and the one place the security\n236\tagent verifies the control lives (`code-standards` facade rule).\n237\t\n238\t- `EXPORT_HEADER = [\"customer_id\", \"metric\", \"window_start\", \"total_quantity\"]` — the brief's\n239\t  exact column order; always written as row 1.\n240\t- `escape_csv_text_cell(value: str) -> str` — the OWASP CSV/formula-injection defense applied\n241\t  to **text** cells only:\n242\t  - If the cell's first character is one of `=  +  -  @  \\t  \\r`, prefix a single quote `'`\n243\t    so a spreadsheet treats it as text, not a formula.\n244\t  - Neutralize embedded control characters (strip/quote) — RFC 4180 quoting via\n245\t    `QUOTE_MINIMAL` already quotes comma/quote/CR/LF; raw control chars are stripped.\n246\t  - *Why this matters even though ingest already validates:* the current ingest allowlist\n247\t    `^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$` **permits a leading `-`** (e.g. a `customer_id` of `-1`), and\n248\t    a leading `-` is a live spreadsheet-formula trigger — so this is not hypothetical. It is\n249\t    deliberately applied **at the sink, independent of upstream validation**: the encoder must\n250\t    stay safe even if the ingest contract later loosens, and defense at the sink is the\n251\t    correct place for output-context injection defenses. The other triggers (`=`,`+`,`@`, tab,\n252\t    CR) cannot appear under today's allowlist but are escaped anyway as defense-in-depth.\n253\t- `total_quantity` is rendered as `str(Decimal)` (brief: plain decimal, no scientific\n254\t  notation — `Numeric(38,6)` values never render in `E` notation via `str()`; scale-6\n255\t  trailing zeros are preserved, which is deterministic and diff-clean). `window_start` is\n256\t  rendered as `.isoformat()` (UTC ISO-8601 with offset — byte-identical to the JSON\n257\t  response's string form). **Numeric and timestamp cells are server-generated and are not\n258\t  passed through the formula escape** (they are never attacker-controlled and escaping them\n259\t  would corrupt the value).\n260\t\n261\tThe generator (in the service) owns the `csv.writer`/`StringIO` mechanics and calls\n262\t`escape_csv_text_cell` on `customer_id` and `metric` before `writerow`. Browser safety is\n263\tbelt-and-suspenders: the existing `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` header plus\n264\t`Content-Disposition: attachment` mean a browser downloads the CSV rather than rendering it,\n265\tso there is no browser-side injection surface either.\n266\t\n267\t## Data / migrations\n268\t\n269\t**No migration.** The feature is a read over the existing `usage_rollup` table; it adds no\n270\ttable, column, index, constraint, or data-classification surface (brief resolved: \"None —\n271\tread-only feature\"). `usage_rollup`'s primary key is `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n272\twindow_start)`.\n273\t\n274\t*Ordering vs. index — the one real data tradeoff (Open Question 2).* The brief calls the\n275\texport ordering \"index-friendly,\" but the requested `ORDER BY window_start, customer_id,\n276\tmetric` for a fixed `api_key_id` does **not** align with the PK's `(customer_id, metric,\n277\twindow_start)` intra-key order, so PostgreSQL will do a bounded in-memory/on-disk **sort** of\n278\tthe (≤100,000, capped) matching rows rather than a pure index-ordered scan. Two options:\n279\t\n280\t- **(A) Add a covering index `(api_key_id, window_start, customer_id, metric)`** → makes the\n281\t  ORDER BY an index scan, cheapest possible export. *Rejected for this slice:* it is a\n282\t  migration (contradicts the brief's no-migration resolution) **and** every hot-path\n283\t  `usage_rollup` upsert on `POST /v1/events` would then have to maintain a second index — a\n284\t  small but real write cost on exactly the path the brief says must not change (\"POST\n285\t  /v1/events' budget, tests, and code path are untouched\").\n286\t- **(B) No index; accept a bounded sort of ≤100k rows (chosen).** Respects both the\n287\t  no-migration and no-ingest-change constraints and adds zero write cost to ingest. A 100k-row\n288\t  sort is well within a 500 ms reporting p95. The `api_key_id` PK-prefix still bounds the scan\n289\t  to the caller's rows. If the p95 sanity check (AC16) fails at the cap, the follow-up is\n290\t  option (A) in its own migration — surfaced at the checkpoint, not silently taken.\n291\t\n292\t**RLS-backstop efficacy note (honest, and an existing condition — not changed here).**\n293\tTenant isolation's **primary** control is the explicit `api_key_id` filter every export query\n294\tincludes; the PostgreSQL `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation` RLS policy (migration 0002) is the\n295\tbackstop. That policy is `ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` **without `FORCE`**, and the app role\n296\t(`meterly_app`) owns the table — a table owner bypasses non-`FORCE` RLS, so the backstop is\n297\teffectively **inert for the app role** on `usage_rollup` today. This pre-exists and affects\n298\t`GET /v1/usage` identically; the export does not worsen it. The export's isolation therefore\n299\trests on the mandatory explicit filter (which the streaming and count queries both carry), not\n300\ton RLS. Recommended follow-up (outside this no-migration slice): a migration adding `ALTER\n301\tTABLE usage_rollup FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY`, mirroring what 0003 did for `quotas` — raised as\n302\tOpen Question 3, not built here.\n303\t\n304\t## Auth & authorization\n305\t\n306\t- **Authentication:** `require_api_key` (existing split-token + Argon2id-verify facade) gates\n307\t  the route; a missing/invalid/revoked key → 401 before the handler runs. Unchanged mechanism.\n308\t- **Authorization:** intentionally **any authenticated key** (ingest or admin) may export its\n309\t  own tenant's data — same read authority as `GET /v1/usage`, no `scope` gate (brief: admin-only\n310\t  gating is out of scope). The only access-control boundary is tenant isolation, enforced by the\n311\t  mandatory `api_key_id = principal.api_key_id` filter on every query (the caller can only ever\n312\t  read its own rollups — IDOR/BOLA closed). `api_key_id` is sourced from the authenticated\n313\t  principal and is **never** accepted from the request (no schema field, `extra=\"forbid\"`) — the\n314\t  mass-assignment defense against reading another tenant.\n315\t- **Throttle:** the Tier-2 **per-`api_key_id`** token bucket (post-auth, principal-keyed) is the\n316\t  binding rate limit for this authenticated route — correctly keyed on identity, so two tenants\n317\t  behind one NAT IP get independent buckets. (The pre-auth Tier-1 IP throttle also applies but is\n318\t  secondary here; its client-IP-behind-ALB derivation is an existing app-wide condition, not one\n319\t  this feature introduces or depends on for its protection.)\n320\t\n321\t## Logging\n322\t\n323\tOne new observable event through the existing `get_logger()` facade (a Read/CRUD audit event):\n324\t\n325\t- **`usage.export`** at `info`, emitted at generator completion (`finally`): `operation=\n326\t  \"usage.export\"`, `userId=<api_key_id>` (opaque internal integer, not PII), `action=\"read\"`,\n327\t  `resource=\"usage_rollup\"`, `rowCount`, `capped` (bool), `completed` (bool), and **filter\n328\t  presence as booleans** (`filtered_by_customer`, `filtered_by_metric`, `bounded_from`,\n329\t  `bounded_to`) — never the raw `customer_id`/`metric` values. The centralized redaction\n330\t  processor scrubs `customer_id` regardless; logging booleans is belt-and-suspenders and keeps\n331\t  the 5W+H answerable without PII.\n332\t- **`usage.export.rejected`** at `warn` on an over-cap request (`reason=\"row_cap_exceeded\"`) —\n333\t  a validation-boundary event and a useful signal (a caller repeatedly requesting oversized\n334\t  exports).\n335\t\n336\t5W+H check: Who = `userId` (opaque `api_key_id`); What = `usage.export` / `read` /\n337\t`usage_rollup`; When = logger timestamp; Where = `service` + `requestId`/`traceId` (bound by the\n338\trequest-context middleware); How = `GET /v1/usage/export`. No new SLO/alarm for this reporting\n339\tslice.\n340\t\n341\t## Infrastructure\n342\t\n343\tNo `infra/` change. No provisioned resource, no new secret (the export reuses the existing DB\n344\tcredential via the existing secrets facade), no new IAM. The route ships through the existing\n345\tCI → build-provenance → deploy chain. Operability note (carried from the Backend section): the\n346\tstreaming server-side cursor holds a pooled DB connection for the client-download duration,\n347\tbounded by the row cap + Tier-2 throttle + pool sizing (accepted risk R1).\n348\t\n349\t## Input sources (for security's input-surface reconciliation)\n350\t\n351\tThis feature exposes exactly **one** input source:\n352\t\n353\t1. **`GET /v1/usage/export` query parameters** — `customer_id`, `metric`, `from`, `to` (all\n354\t   optional). The `Authorization` header is an input too but is validated by the existing auth\n355\t   facade (unchanged). Controls for this source:\n356\t   - **Validation (AC4, non-waivable):** `UsageExportQueryParams` — anchored allowlist `constr`\n357\t     for `customer_id`/`metric`, `AwareDatetime` + range/order bounds for `from`/`to`,\n358\t     `extra=\"forbid\"`. Malformed / wrong-type / unknown / out-of-range → 422 `validation_failed`.\n359\t     Output-encoding-at-sink: values reach a **SQL** sink (parameterized, never concatenated)\n360\t     and a **CSV** sink (formula-escaped at the encoding boundary).\n361\t   - **Rate limit (AC5):** principal-keyed **Tier-2** per-`api_key_id` throttle (per-owner\n362\t     resource → key dimension is the authenticated principal, existing default limit, per-second\n363\t     window). Discriminating test: two principals on one IP get independent buckets.\n364\t\n365\t## Files affected\n366\t\n367\tSource (new):\n368\t- `src/api/routes/usage_export.py` — new `GET /v1/usage/export` route (auth+throttle sibling,\n369\t  two-phase cap-then-stream, StreamingResponse, OpenAPI `responses=` metadata).\n370\t- `src/api/schemas/usage_export.py` — `UsageExportQueryParams` (optional filters, `from` alias,\n371\t  range/order validation, `extra=\"forbid\"`).\n372\t- `src/services/usage_export_service.py` — `prepare_export` (cap check + fail-closed non-cap\n373\t  error propagation) + `stream_export_csv` (server-side-cursor streaming generator,\n374\t  header-first, audit log).\n375\t- `src/api/csv_export.py` — CSV column contract + `escape_csv_text_cell` (OWASP formula/control\n376\t  escape), value formatting helpers.\n377\t\n378\tSource (extend; existing functions untouched):\n379\t- `src/repositories/usage_repo.py` — add `UsageRollupExportRecord`, `count_usage_rollups`,\n380\t  `stream_usage_rollups`.\n381\t- `src/main.py` — register the new router (one `include_router` line; nothing else changes).\n382\t\n383\tDocs (touched-dir updates, per \"done means\"):\n384\t- `src/api/README.md`, `src/services/README.md`, `src/repositories/README.md` — add the export\n385\t  route/service/repo entries. `docs/system_architecture.md` — note the export flow.\n386\t\n387\tTests:\n388\t- `tests/test_csv_export.py` — unit: formula escape (incl. leading-`-` `customer_id`), control\n389\t  chars, RFC 4180 quoting (comma/quote/newline), CRLF, numeric/timestamp untouched, value\n390\t  formatting.\n391\t- `tests/test_schemas_usage_export.py` — unit: optional filters, `from` alias, `from<=to`,\n392\t  `[now-90d, now+1h]` bounds, naive rejected, `extra=\"forbid\"`.\n393\t- `tests/test_usage_export_service.py` — unit: header-first empty result, cap → 422, audit-log\n394\t  fields (no raw `customer_id`), completion in `finally` on disconnect, **pre-flight non-cap DB\n395\t  error propagates (not swallowed, no stream started) → AC22**.\n396\t- `tests/integration/test_usage_export_endpoint.py` — integration (testcontainers Postgres):\n397\t  200 header-only empty, filters, deterministic ordering, tenant isolation (two tenants), cap\n398\t  422 no partial body, formula-escape end-to-end, response headers, streaming-not-buffered\n399\t  sanity, OpenAPI-schema-includes-route, **forced pre-flight `COUNT` error → generic `500\n400\t  internal` envelope with no stack/SQL leak and no partial CSV body (AC22)**.\n401\t- `tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py` — integration: p95 timing sanity at ~100k rows\n402\t  (AC16; a timing assertion, not a k6 load AC).\n403\t\n404\t## Test strategy\n405\t\n406\t**`pyramid`** (the default; no rationale-for-deviation needed). The bulk of the logic — CSV\n407\tformula-escaping and RFC 4180 quoting, schema validation and range/alias handling, value\n408\tformatting, cap arithmetic, header-first/empty handling — is pure and unit-tested. A thinner\n409\tintegration tier carries the correctness that cannot be faithfully mocked: the server-side\n410\tstreaming cursor, deterministic ordering, tenant isolation, the pre-flight cap 422, the\n411\tpre-flight safe-error path (AC22), response headers, and the streaming-not-buffered behavior,\n412\tall against a real PostgreSQL via testcontainers. This bias is a tier-priority hint for the\n413\ttesting agent; it does not relax the project's ≥85% coverage gate.\n414\t\n415\t## Open questions\n416\t\n417\t1. **Documented p95 target for the export route** (the brief's one `Open` item). *Proposed\n418\t   default:* p95 < 500 ms at the 100,000-row cap, verified by the AC16 integration timing sanity\n419\t   check (not a k6 load AC — this is a reporting route, and the binding perf criterion is the\n420\t   negative one: `POST /v1/events`'s budget/tests/code path stay untouched). Confirm or adjust\n421\t   the number at the checkpoint.\n422\t2. **Ordering index.** Proposed: **no new index** (option B) — accept a bounded sort of ≤100k\n423\t   rows to honor the no-migration + no-ingest-change constraints; add the covering index in a\n424\t   follow-up only if AC16 fails. Confirm the tradeoff.\n425\t3. **`usage_rollup` RLS `FORCE` (pre-existing gap).** The RLS backstop is inert for the app-owner\n426\t   role on `usage_rollup` (no `FORCE`); isolation rests on the explicit `api_key_id` filter.\n427\t   Proposed: keep the explicit-filter control for this slice (no migration) and file a follow-up\n428\t   migration adding `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` (as 0003 did for `quotas`). Confirm the deferral.\n429\t\n430\t## Acceptance-criteria trace (CLAUDE.md \"What done means\" → plan)\n431\t\n432\t- *Smoke check passes* → ✓ additive route; `import src.main` stays dependency-free (deferred DB/\n433\t  Redis unchanged); `/health` liveness untouched.\n434\t- *Security report clean* → ✓ Threat Model + ASVS Compliance below; every mitigation names a\n435\t  concrete mechanism + file; input-surface controls enumerated.\n436\t- *Tests pass ≥85% coverage* → ✓ Test strategy above (unit + integration tiers).\n437\t- *Docs updated for touched directories* → ✓ README/architecture updates in Files affected.\n438\t- *PR description written* → downstream (documentation stage).\n439\t\n440\tFeature-level definition-of-done is enumerated in `.pipeline/acceptance.md` (22 criteria,\n441\t`AC18` delegated to security).\n442\t\n443\t## Threat Model\n444\t\n445\t### Assets and trust boundaries\n446\t\n447\t**Assets:** the caller's `usage_rollup` rows (billing-adjacent, `customer_id` is\n448\tpersonal-class data); the exported CSV file (an injection carrier once opened in a\n449\tspreadsheet); the authenticated tenant identity (`api_key_id`); the pooled DB\n450\tconnection/transaction held during streaming.\n451\t\n452\t**Trust boundaries:**\n453\t- **Client ↔ API** (HTTP): the export request + streamed CSV response.\n454\t- **API ↔ PostgreSQL** (app ↔ datastore): the count + streaming queries.\n455\t- **CSV file ↔ downstream spreadsheet app** (a *new* boundary this feature introduces): the\n456\t  exported file may be opened in Excel/Sheets, where an unescaped formula-leading cell would\n457\t  execute.\n458\t\n459\tNo `infra/` change → no cloud attack-surface section (nothing provisioned).\n460\t\n461\t### ASVS Compliance\n462\t\n463\t**Triggered chapters (L1 + L2 universal):** V1 Encoding & Sanitization (CSV/formula output\n464\tencoding), V2 Validation & Anti-automation (query validation + throttle/DoS), V4 API, V6\n465\tAuthentication (reused API-key path), V8 Authorization (tenant isolation / BOLA), V13\n466\tConfiguration (docs exposure, least-privilege), V14 Data Protection (no-store caching, minimal\n467\tprojection, no tenant id in filename), V16 Security Logging & Error Handling.\n468\t\n469\t**Not triggered / n/a:** V5 File Handling — the feature *emits* a CSV but accepts **no file\n470\tupload**, so upload-validation items are n/a. V7 Session Management, V9 Self-contained Tokens,\n471\tV10 OAuth/OIDC — n/a (stateless API-key auth, no session/JWT/OAuth). V11 Cryptography — no new\n472\tcrypto (Argon2id verify is reused via the auth path, not extended here). V12 Secure\n473\tCommunication — TLS terminates at the ALB (infra), inherited, nothing new. V3/V15 — no new web\n474\tfrontend or unsafe-coding surface beyond the encoding covered by V1.\n475\t\n476\t**In-scope L3:** none new for this feature. It inherits the project's existing L3 item\n477\t(11.2.4 constant-time comparison) transitively through the reused auth path; the export adds no\n478\tnew L3-warranting surface.\n479\t\n480\t**Waivers (L1/L2 code/config items genuinely N/A here):**\n481\t- `{id: 5.x (V5 file upload validation), reason: feature accepts no file upload — it generates\n482\t  a download}`\n483\t- `{id: 7.x / 9.x / 10.x (session/token/OAuth), reason: stateless API-key auth, no session or\n484\t  bearer-JWT lifecycle in this feature}`\n485\t\n486\t### STRIDE table\n487\t\n488\t| Category | Asset / Boundary | Attack vector | Sev | Mitigation (mechanism + file) | ASVS |\n489\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n490\t| Spoofing | Client ↔ API | Unauthenticated / forged caller exports a tenant's data | M | `require_api_key` dependency (split-token + Argon2id verify, 401 on any failure) on the route — `src/api/routes/usage_export.py` reusing `src/auth`; identical to existing endpoints | 6.2.x, 7.x |\n491\t| Tampering | API ↔ PostgreSQL | Injection via `customer_id`/`metric`/`from`/`to` into the WHERE/ORDER BY | M | `UsageExportQueryParams` anchored-allowlist `constr` + `AwareDatetime`+bounds, `extra=\"forbid\"` — `src/api/schemas/usage_export.py`; **bound-parameter** SQL (`text()` + params, no concat) and a **fixed literal** ORDER BY (never client-derived) — `src/repositories/usage_repo.py` | 1.2.x, 2.2.x |\n492\t| Tampering | CSV ↔ spreadsheet | Malicious ingested identifier (e.g. leading `-`) becomes a live formula when the export is opened in Excel/Sheets by a downstream user | M | `escape_csv_text_cell` prefixes `'` when a text cell starts with `= + - @ \\t \\r`, strips control chars, leaves numeric/timestamp cells untouched — `src/api/csv_export.py`; **enabling condition:** applied at the CSV **sink** independent of ingest validation (the ingest allowlist already permits leading `-`), on `customer_id`+`metric` only; plus `Content-Disposition: attachment` + existing `nosniff` so browsers download, not render | 1.3.x |\n493\t| Repudiation | Client ↔ API | Caller denies performing a bulk export of tenant data | L | One `usage.export` structured audit log at completion (who=`userId`/opaque `api_key_id`, what/when/where/how, `rowCount`, `capped`, `completed`) in the generator `finally` — `src/services/usage_export_service.py` via `src/logging` | 16.2.x, 16.3.x |\n494\t| Info Disclosure | API ↔ PostgreSQL / Client ↔ API | Over-broad response leaking another tenant's rollups | M | **Mandatory** `api_key_id = principal.api_key_id` filter on the count + stream queries (primary control) — `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`; `api_key_id` sourced server-side, never from the request (`extra=\"forbid\"`); RLS policy is a backstop whose app-role efficacy needs `FORCE` (pre-existing gap, Open Q3) — **enabling condition:** isolation relies on the explicit filter, not RLS | 8.2.x, 14.3.x |\n495\t| Info Disclosure | Client ↔ API / logs / errors | PII (`customer_id`) or internals leaking via logs, error bodies, filename, or caching | M | Minimal 4-column projection (`UsageRollupExportRecord`) — `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`; centralized redaction processor + booleans-not-values in the audit log — `src/logging` + `src/services/usage_export_service.py`; error-envelope facade returns generic `internal` on any unexpected error (incl. a **pre-flight `COUNT`** failure — fail-closed, no stack/SQL/internal path, AC22) — `src/api/errors.py`; filename carries only a UTC timestamp (no tenant id) — `src/api/routes/usage_export.py`; existing `Cache-Control: no-store` — `src/api/middleware.py` | 14.3.2, 16.5.x |\n496\t| Denial of Service | API + PostgreSQL | Unbounded result / expensive sort / slow-client connection-hold exhausts memory, CPU, or the pool | M | Pre-flight `count_usage_rollups` → 422 over 100k **before any body byte** + `LIMIT 100000` on the stream — `src/services/usage_export_service.py` + `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`; constant-memory server-side-cursor streaming (one row buffered) — generator in the service; **enabling condition:** the binding throttle is the post-auth **Tier-2 per-`api_key_id`** bucket (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`, existing) — correctly identity-keyed, so it actually limits per-caller export concurrency; connection-hold bounded by cap + throttle + pool (accepted risk R1) | 2.4.x, 4.x |\n497\t| Elevation of Privilege | Client ↔ API | Client supplies `api_key_id`/`scope` to read another tenant or gain admin capability | M | `api_key_id`/`scope` are **absent** from the request schema and `extra=\"forbid\"` rejects them; `api_key_id` comes only from the authenticated principal — `src/api/schemas/usage_export.py` + `src/services/usage_export_service.py`; export is intentionally not scope-gated, so there is no privilege to escalate | 8.2.x, 15.3.3 |\n498\t\n499\t### Severity notes / accepted risks (out of scope for this slice)\n500\t\n501\t- **R1 — slow-client connection-hold** (DoS row): a slow reader pins a pooled DB connection for\n502\t  the download. Accepted: bounded by the 100k cap + Tier-2 throttle + pool sizing; batched keyset\n503\t  pagination is the future mitigation if it bites.\n504\t- **R2 — `usage_rollup` RLS not `FORCE`** (Info-Disclosure backstop): inert for the app-owner\n505\t  role; isolation rests on the explicit `api_key_id` filter. Pre-existing, affects `GET /v1/usage`\n506\t  equally; follow-up migration recommended (Open Q3), not built here.\n507\t- **R3 — post-200 mid-stream failure truncates the CSV** rather than returning a clean error\n508\t  envelope: once `200` + body bytes are on the wire, the envelope can no longer apply. Accepted\n509\t  and **strictly the post-200 case** — the *pre-flight* `COUNT` phase runs before any response\n510\t  byte and **is** cleanly recoverable (generic `500 internal` envelope, no partial body), which\n511\t  is covered by AC22, not accepted here. The dominant explicit failure mode (oversized result)\n512\t  is caught cleanly by the pre-flight 422; a rare mid-stream DB error yields a truncated download\n513\t  the client re-requests. Out of scope: CSV trailer/checksum.\n514\t- Out of scope per the brief (not threats, exclusions): pagination, admin-only gating, other\n515\t  formats/compression/async export jobs, any change to existing endpoints, per-export audit\n516\t  logging beyond the one structured event above.\n517\t\n518\t### Threat-model diagram (Mermaid DFD)\n519\t\n520\t```mermaid\n521\tflowchart TD\n522\t    Caller[API-key client]\n523\t    Sheet[\"Downstream spreadsheet app ⚠ CSV-formula sink\"]\n524\t\n525\t    subgraph edge[\"Trust boundary: Meterly API (ECS Fargate)\"]\n526\t        Auth(require_api_key + Tier-2 per-key throttle)\n527\t        Route(GET /v1/usage/export handler)\n528\t        Cap(prepare_export: pre-flight count cap → 422 / fail-closed 500)\n529\t        Stream(\"stream_export_csv: server-side-cursor streaming ⚠\")\n530\t        Csv(csv_export: formula-escape + RFC 4180)\n531\t    end\n532\t\n533\t    subgraph data[\"Trust boundary: PostgreSQL (RDS)\"]\n534\t        Rollup[(\"usage_rollup ⚠ api_key_id-scoped read\")]\n535\t    end\n536\t\n537\t    Caller -- \"Bearer mtr_live_… + query filters\" --> Auth\n538\t    Auth -- authenticated principal --> Route\n539\t    Route -- api_key_id + filters --> Cap\n540\t    Cap -- \"COUNT(*) scoped by api_key_id\" --> Rollup\n541\t    Cap -- \"422 if > 100k rows / 500 internal on error (no body)\" --> Caller\n542\t    Route -- api_key_id + filters --> Stream\n543\t    Stream -- \"streamed SELECT (scoped, ORDER BY, LIMIT 100000)\" --> Rollup\n544\t    Stream -- rows --> Csv\n545\t    Csv -- \"escaped CSV rows (text/csv, attachment)\" --> Caller\n546\t    Caller -. \"opens file\" .-> Sheet\n547\t```\n548\t\n549\t### Copy-paste visualization prompt\n550\t\n551\t```text\n552\tYou are a threat-modeling assistant. Build a data-flow diagram with trust boundaries for this\n553\tfeature.\n554\t\n555\tFEATURE: GET /v1/usage/export — a read-only endpoint on the Meterly usage-metering API\n556\t(Python/FastAPI on AWS ECS Fargate, PostgreSQL/RDS). It streams the authenticated API-key\n557\tcaller's own usage_rollup rows as an RFC 4180 CSV (columns: customer_id, metric, window_start,\n558\ttotal_quantity), with optional customer_id/metric/from/to filters, a hard 100,000-row cap, and\n559\tOWASP CSV-formula-injection escaping.\n560\t\n561\tASSETS: the caller's usage_rollup rows (billing-adjacent; customer_id is personal-class data);\n562\tthe exported CSV file (an injection carrier once opened in a spreadsheet); the tenant identity\n563\t(api_key_id); the pooled DB connection/transaction held open during streaming.\n564\t\n565\tTRUST BOUNDARIES: Client <-> API (HTTP); API <-> PostgreSQL (app <-> datastore); CSV file <->\n566\tdownstream spreadsheet application (formula-injection boundary).\n567\t\n568\tSTRIDE THREATS (category | asset/boundary | vector | severity | mitigation + concrete mechanism):\n569\t- Spoofing | Client<->API | unauthenticated/forged caller exports tenant data | Medium |\n570\t  require_api_key (split-token + Argon2id verify, 401 on failure) on the route.\n571\t- Tampering | API<->PostgreSQL | injection via query params into WHERE/ORDER BY | Medium |\n572\t  Pydantic anchored-allowlist validation + extra=forbid; bound-parameter SQL; fixed-literal\n573\t  ORDER BY never derived from client input.\n574\t- Tampering | CSV<->spreadsheet | ingested identifier with a leading =,+,-,@,tab,CR becomes a\n575\t  live formula in Excel/Sheets | Medium | escape_csv_text_cell prefixes ' on formula-leading\n576\t  text cells and strips control chars, applied at the CSV sink independent of ingest\n577\t  validation, on customer_id+metric only; Content-Disposition: attachment + nosniff.\n578\t- Repudiation | Client<->API | caller denies a bulk export | Low | one usage.export structured\n579\t  audit log at completion (who/what/when/where/how, rowCount, capped, completed).\n580\t- Information Disclosure | API<->PostgreSQL | over-broad response leaks another tenant's rows |\n581\t  Medium | mandatory api_key_id filter on every query (primary control); api_key_id sourced\n582\t  server-side, never from the request; RLS backstop (efficacy needs FORCE — pre-existing gap).\n583\t- Information Disclosure | Client<->API/logs/errors | customer_id PII or internals leak via\n584\t  logs/errors/filename/cache | Medium | minimal 4-column projection; log redaction + booleans\n585\t  not raw values; error-envelope facade returns generic \"internal\" on any unexpected error\n586\t  including a pre-flight COUNT failure (fail-closed, no stack/SQL, no partial body); filename\n587\t  is a UTC timestamp only; Cache-Control: no-store.\n588\t- Denial of Service | API + PostgreSQL | unbounded result / expensive sort / slow-client\n589\t  connection-hold | Medium | pre-flight COUNT -> 422 over 100k before any body byte + LIMIT\n590\t  100000; constant-memory server-side-cursor streaming; post-auth Tier-2 per-api_key_id\n591\t  throttle bounds per-caller export concurrency.\n592\t- Elevation of Privilege | Client<->API | client supplies api_key_id/scope to cross tenants |\n593\t  Medium | api_key_id/scope absent from the schema, extra=forbid rejects them; api_key_id from\n594\t  the authenticated principal only; export is not scope-gated (nothing to escalate).\n595\t\n596\tRender this as an OWASP Threat Dragon diagram. Output either (a) valid Threat Dragon JSON\n597\timportable at app.threatdragon.com, or (b) a labeled data flow diagram with trust boundaries if\n598\tJSON is not feasible. No additional context is available beyond what is in this prompt.\n599\t```\n600\t\n601\t## Revision notes\n602\t\n603\tSingle revision pass in response to `.pipeline/plan-audit.md` (2 material flags,\n604\t`revision_recommended: true`). Both material flags addressed; no advisory flags were present.\n605\tScope was not expanded beyond resolving the flags.\n606\t\n607\t- **[material] `tasks.md` not emitted vs. the decomposition trigger.** The audit applied the\n608\t  *old* two-legged trigger (≥25 files **OR** ≥15 criteria) and flagged that `criteria_total: 21`\n609\t  met the criteria leg. Per the coordinator, the engine's current contract has **retired the\n610\t  ≥15-criteria leg**; the decomposition trigger is now the **single ≥25-estimated-files leg**.\n611\t  Resolution: corrected the plan's wording rather than emitting a decomposition. The frontmatter\n612\t  `tasks_file_emitted` comment now states the single-leg trigger explicitly, notes the retired\n613\t  criteria leg, and justifies the no-`tasks.md` call on the ~14-file estimate (below 25) — so\n614\t  the criteria count (now 22) is correctly *not* a trigger. No `tasks.md` is emitted.\n615\t- **[material] Missing safe-error AC for the pre-flight phase.** Added **AC22** to\n616\t  `.pipeline/acceptance.md`: a forced internal error during the pre-flight `prepare_export`\n617\t  `COUNT` phase must return the generic `500 internal` error-envelope (no stack/SQL/internal\n618\t  path leaked), fail closed with the transaction rolled back, and **start no stream / emit no\n619\t  partial body**. Updated `criteria_total: 21 → 22` (frontmatter and the \"22 criteria\" reference\n620\t  in the plan body); `delegated_criteria` unchanged (`[AC18]`). Traced AC22 to two tests — a unit\n621\t  test in `tests/test_usage_export_service.py` (the non-cap DB error propagates, is not\n622\t  swallowed, no stream started) and an integration test in\n623\t  `tests/integration/test_usage_export_endpoint.py` (forced pre-flight `COUNT` error → generic\n624\t  `500 internal` envelope, no leak, no partial CSV). Strengthened the plan text in three places:\n625\t  the route two-phase description (point 1 now spells out the fail-closed non-cap error path),\n626\t  the `prepare_export` bullet (non-cap exceptions deliberately propagate, not swallowed), and the\n627\t  accepted-risk **R3** (now scoped *strictly* to the post-200 mid-stream case, explicitly\n628\t  distinguishing the cleanly-recoverable pre-flight phase covered by AC22). The Info-Disclosure\n629\t  STRIDE row and the copy-paste prompt now name the pre-flight fail-closed error shape as part of\n630\t  the error-envelope mitigation (ASVS 16.5.x). Updated the Mermaid DFD Cap node/edge to show the\n631\t  `500 internal on error (no body)` outcome alongside the `422`.\n632\t"}]},"uuid":"d59faad2-41a4-452c-87c9-2398a078e3dc","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:10:46.677Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"718b1d71-9db8-4896-98bb-16b1b4a8d378","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
