{"parentUuid":"690122e3-0f1b-4811-a05e-ec565815cb29","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcrwBA1wgaswdE9vZSqcz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EfjZ9VZnGJsYWTDGbpYb56","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd \"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\" && git diff PROJECT.md | head -50"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":351,"cache_read_input_tokens":80743,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":351,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcrwB93u7Sam2pP4kqeK7","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"1cf7d70c-d67b-4f98-b07d-e3899320869d","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:39.304Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"1cf7d70c-d67b-4f98-b07d-e3899320869d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EfjZ9VZnGJsYWTDGbpYb56","type":"tool_result","content":"diff --git a/PROJECT.md b/PROJECT.md\nindex ef22d91..bc052b4 100644\n--- a/PROJECT.md\n+++ b/PROJECT.md\n@@ -1,6 +1,4 @@\n-Feature: per-customer metric quotas.\n-- PUT /v1/quotas (admin-scoped API key) sets {customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}.\n-- POST /v1/events returns 429 with a quota error envelope when the current-window rollup for that customer/metric would exceed the quota. Customers without a quota are unlimited (no behavior change).\n-- One expand-only migration: a quotas table.\n-- Existing perf budget applies: p95 < 50 ms under load on POST /v1/events.\n+Feature: usage CSV export.\n+- GET /v1/usage/export returns the caller's usage rollups (customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity) as CSV.\n+- Existing API-key auth applies. No behavior change to any existing endpoint.\n Design source: none.","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"1e08a70e-c6a7-4edb-8ab2-ac044768a582","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:39.880Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1cf7d70c-d67b-4f98-b07d-e3899320869d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"1e08a70e-c6a7-4edb-8ab2-ac044768a582","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcrwBA1wgaswdE9vZSqcz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017f5woxTY6rQ5T9dHHwRMq8","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\src\\api\\README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":351,"cache_read_input_tokens":80743,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":351,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcrwB93u7Sam2pP4kqeK7","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"b00c3575-e334-48c0-a4d6-bcf685c529d5","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:40.032Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"b00c3575-e334-48c0-a4d6-bcf685c529d5","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017f5woxTY6rQ5T9dHHwRMq8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# src/api/\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tHTTP API layer: FastAPI route handlers, request/response schemas (Pydantic v2), error envelope boundary, and edge-concern middleware (request ID, security headers, CORS, body-size guards).\n6\t\n7\t## Modules\n8\t\n9\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| `routes/events.py` | `POST /v1/events` handler; calls `events_service.create_event`. |\n12\t| `routes/usage.py` | `GET /v1/usage` handler; calls `usage_service.read_usage`. |\n13\t| `routes/quotas.py` | `PUT /v1/quotas` handler; composes auth -> Tier-2 throttle -> an `admin`-scope gate (403 `forbidden` otherwise) -> `quota_service.upsert_tenant_quota`. |\n14\t| `routes/health.py` | `GET /health` (liveness, no dependencies) and `GET /health/ready` (readiness, DB + migration check). |\n15\t| `schemas/events.py` | Pydantic models for POST /v1/events request and response; `extra='forbid'` contract enforcement. |\n16\t| `schemas/usage.py` | Pydantic models for GET /v1/usage request (query parameters) and response. |\n17\t| `schemas/quotas.py` | Pydantic models for PUT /v1/quotas request (`customer_id`, `metric`, `limit_per_window`, `extra='forbid'`) and response (echo shape). |\n18\t| `middleware.py` | Request-ID / trace-ID assignment, security headers (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options), CORS (allows GET/POST/PUT). |\n19\t| `errors.py` | Error-envelope boundary: catches all unhandled exceptions and returns `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` with no stack/secret leakage. `AppError` lets a raised exception carry an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that overrides the default status->code map — needed because 429 is shared by two distinct codes (`rate_limited` vs `quota_exceeded`). |\n20\t\n21\t## Relationships\n22\t\n23\t**Public surface:**\n24\t- Imported by `src/main.py` to register routes with FastAPI.\n25\t- Exposes `get_app()` function which returns the fully-configured FastAPI instance.\n26\t\n27\t**Dependencies:**\n28\t- `middleware.py` and `errors.py` are registered once at app construction (middleware stack + exception handler).\n29\t- Each route handler uses `require_api_key` guard from `src/auth` to enforce authentication.\n30\t- Route handlers call `src/services.{events_service, usage_service}` to execute business logic.\n31\t- Schemas validate request bodies/parameters; malformed input raises Pydantic `ValidationError` → 422.\n32\t- Middleware and error boundary run for all routes, ensuring every response has proper headers and envelope shape.\n33\t\n34\t**Middleware ordering (in `main.py`):**\n35\t1. Request-ID / trace (outermost) — sets correlation context for all downstream logging.\n36\t2. Security headers — applied to every response.\n37\t3. CORS — explicit allowlist from config.\n38\t4. Body-size guard — reject Content-Length > 8 KiB.\n39\t5. Tier-1 edge throttle (pre-auth) — IP+route keyed.\n40\t6. `require_api_key` guard — auth.\n41\t7. Tier-2 per-key throttle (post-auth) — api_key_id keyed.\n42\t8. Route handler (innermost) — wrapped by error-envelope boundary.\n43\t\n44\t## Notes\n45\t\n46\t**Contract enforcement:**\n47\t- Request bodies are validated against Pydantic schemas; `extra='forbid'` rejects unknown fields.\n48\t- All string fields are bounded length (e.g., `customer_id` ≤128, `metric` ≤64).\n49\t- `quantity` is a decimal > 0 (no zero or negative); `idempotency_key` is alphanumeric + underscore/dash.\n50\t- GET `/v1/usage` requires a timezone-aware ISO-8601 `window` parameter within 90 days past to 1 hour future (naive datetimes rejected).\n51\t- PUT `/v1/quotas`: `limit_per_window` is an integer `>= 1` (`<= 1e15`, BIGINT-safe); `customer_id`/`metric` reuse the same anchored allowlists as events; unknown fields (including a client-supplied `api_key_id`/`scope`) are rejected outright.\n52\t\n53\t**Error handling:**\n54\t- Authentication failures (missing/invalid key) → 401/403 before handlers run.\n55\t- `PUT /v1/quotas` from a non-`admin`-scoped key → 403 `forbidden` (function-level authorization, checked in the route's composed dependency).\n56\t- Rate-limit exceeded (Tier-1 or Tier-2) → 429 `rate_limited` + Retry-After header.\n57\t- `POST /v1/events` over its quota → 429 `quota_exceeded` (distinct code, same status) + Retry-After to the next hour boundary; no event/rollup written (transaction rolled back).\n58\t- Schema validation failure → 422 with Pydantic error detail.\n59\t- Database errors (constraint violation, connection drop) → caught by error envelope → 500 (generic message, safe).\n60\t- Any unhandled exception → error envelope → 500, safe, no leak.\n61\t\n62\t**Security headers (all responses):**\n63\t- `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains` (production only; localhost omitted).\n64\t- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` — disable MIME sniffing.\n65\t- `X-Frame-Options: DENY` — no embedding in iframes.\n66\t- `Cache-Control: no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate, max-age=0` (API, not HTML).\n67\t"}]},"uuid":"d02c2be3-c6b2-4220-8033-1ae9a326affb","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:40.086Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b00c3575-e334-48c0-a4d6-bcf685c529d5","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"d02c2be3-c6b2-4220-8033-1ae9a326affb","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcrwBA1wgaswdE9vZSqcz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LkLWHSpe3i7rBBmn8i3S2W","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\src\\services\\README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":351,"cache_read_input_tokens":80743,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":351,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcrwB93u7Sam2pP4kqeK7","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"26fde2dd-222f-46e3-8edb-ad61c101415e","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:40.403Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"26fde2dd-222f-46e3-8edb-ad61c101415e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LkLWHSpe3i7rBBmn8i3S2W","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# src/services/\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tBusiness logic layer: event ingestion (with idempotency and counter atomicity), usage aggregation, and time-window calculations. Orchestrates repositories and enforces domain invariants.\n6\t\n7\t## Modules\n8\t\n9\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| `events_service.py` | `create_event(principal, payload)` — inserts an event, checks the caller's quota (if any) on the winning-insert branch, and increments the hourly counter, all in one transaction; idempotent on `idempotency_key`. Raises `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`) when `R + Q > L`, which rolls back the event insert. Returns the created/replayed event. |\n12\t| `usage_service.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window)` — reads the aggregated counter for a time bucket; returns zeros if the bucket is empty (never 404). |\n13\t| `quota_service.py` | `upsert_tenant_quota(principal, payload)` — create-or-replaces the caller's cap for `(customer_id, metric)` in one transaction; maps the repository's insert-vs-replace signal to 201/200 and logs the `quota.upsert` audit event. |\n14\t| `time_windows.py` | `window_start_utc(ts: datetime)` — floors a timezone-aware timestamp to the hour (UTC); used by all three services. |\n15\t\n16\t## Relationships\n17\t\n18\t**Public surface:**\n19\t- Imported by `src/api.routes.{events, usage, quotas}` to execute the core business operations.\n20\t\n21\t**Dependencies:**\n22\t- `events_service` imports `src/repositories.{events_repo, quotas_repo}` to insert the event, check the quota, and upsert the counter.\n23\t- `usage_service` imports `src/repositories.usage_repo` to read the rollup.\n24\t- `quota_service` imports `src/repositories.quotas_repo` to upsert the cap.\n25\t- All three services receive an authenticated `AuthenticatedPrincipal` from the route handler (set by `require_api_key` guard); `principal.scope` gates `PUT /v1/quotas` at the route layer before `quota_service` ever runs.\n26\t- `time_windows` is imported by `events_service` and `usage_service` to floor timestamps.\n27\t\n28\t**Transaction boundary:**\n29\t- `create_event` wraps the event insert, the quota check, and the rollup upsert in one PostgreSQL transaction (via `src/db/session_context`).\n30\t- This atomicity ensures that if the insert wins (no existing `idempotency_key`) and the quota check passes, the counter increments exactly once.\n31\t- If the insert loses (duplicate key), the quota is never consulted and neither the counter nor any side effect happens — a no-op.\n32\t- If the quota check rejects (`R + Q > L`), raising `QuotaExceededError` propagates out of the transaction context and rolls it back — the event insert is undone and the counter is never touched (no partial write).\n33\t- `upsert_tenant_quota` wraps the quota upsert in its own transaction; a single `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0)` reports create-vs-replace with no second round-trip.\n34\t\n35\t## Notes\n36\t\n37\t**Idempotency guarantee:**\n38\t- The unique constraint `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` on the `events` table is the source of truth.\n39\t- Exactly one of N concurrent identical requests will succeed; the rest get a duplicate-key constraint violation (caught, no exception raised to handler) and fall through to a replay branch.\n40\t- The replay branch reads the original event from the table and returns it, so the caller sees a consistent result across retries.\n41\t- Recorded in the plan as the **AC-CONCURRENCY** mechanism: 50 concurrent same-key POSTs produce exactly one row and 49 get the replay response (200 vs. 201).\n42\t\n43\t**Counter atomicity:**\n44\t- The event insert and the rollup upsert are in one transaction, so both commit or both roll back.\n45\t- This means a counter never gets incremented without the event being persisted (no partial writes).\n46\t- Also means a duplicate event never increments the counter (no double-counting).\n47\t- The counter uses `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` with `total_quantity + EXCLUDED.total_quantity` to handle the increment (PostgreSQL's row-level conflict resolution, atomic at the SQL level).\n48\t\n49\t**Time-window semantics:**\n50\t- A timestamp is floored to its hour (UTC) to get the `window_start`. E.g., `2026-07-06T14:35:42Z` → `2026-07-06T14:00:00Z`.\n51\t- The floor is done explicitly in Python (`ts.replace(minute=0, second=0, microsecond=0)`) rather than in the database, because PostgreSQL's `date_trunc('hour', ts)` is STABLE (depends on session timezone), not IMMUTABLE, so it cannot be used in a stored generated column.\n52\t- All windows are in UTC; clients must provide timezone-aware ISO-8601 timestamps on GET.\n53\t\n54\t**Scoping by api_key_id:**\n55\t- Both services receive the authenticated `api_key_id` from the route guard (set in `request.state`).\n56\t- Both services pass it to the repository layer, which includes it in the WHERE clause (e.g., `WHERE api_key_id = :auth_key AND customer_id = :customer_id`).\n57\t- This is the primary RLS mechanism; the PostgreSQL RLS policy is the backstop.\n58\t"}]},"uuid":"5fae8513-bff7-4064-9300-341e27e8e76c","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:40.447Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"26fde2dd-222f-46e3-8edb-ad61c101415e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"5fae8513-bff7-4064-9300-341e27e8e76c","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcrwBA1wgaswdE9vZSqcz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Eoh7k6VafwWXhe4MWZYf3n","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\src\\repositories\\README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":351,"cache_read_input_tokens":80743,"output_tokens":591,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":351},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":591,"cache_read_input_tokens":80743,"cache_creation_input_tokens":351,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":351,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcrwB93u7Sam2pP4kqeK7","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"45222c1f-b25e-4ca9-b6bf-5d5ad5069427","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:40.811Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"45222c1f-b25e-4ca9-b6bf-5d5ad5069427","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Eoh7k6VafwWXhe4MWZYf3n","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# src/repositories/\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tData access layer: SQL queries with parameterization, row-level scoping (by authenticated `api_key_id`), and minimal-field projections. All database I/O is encapsulated here.\n6\t\n7\t## Modules\n8\t\n9\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| `events_repo.py` | `create_or_replay_event(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO NOTHING (idempotency). Also `upsert_rollup()` (called only on insert success). |\n12\t| `usage_repo.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). |\n13\t| `api_keys_repo.py` | `find_active_key_by_key_id(key_id)` — SELECT from `api_keys` by public `key_id` (used by auth cache miss); returns the full row including `scope`. `create_api_key(..., scope=\"ingest\")` — the only key-provisioning path. |\n14\t| `quotas_repo.py` | `upsert_quota(...)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted`, reporting create-vs-replace in one round-trip. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(...)` — the atomic check-then-decide: locks the quota row (`FOR UPDATE`), then reads the current-window rollup total as a **separate, fresh** statement (see *Notes* below for why). Returns `None` when no quota exists (unlimited, no lock taken). |\n15\t\n16\t## Relationships\n17\t\n18\t**Public surface:**\n19\t- Imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, quota_service}` to execute queries.\n20\t- `api_keys_repo` is also imported by `src/auth.api_key` (credential lookup on cache miss).\n21\t- `quotas_repo` is imported by both `quota_service` (the upsert) and `events_service` (the read-and-decide).\n22\t\n23\t**Dependencies:**\n24\t- All functions are async; they receive an `AsyncSession` from the service layer (obtained via `src/db.session_context`).\n25\t- Queries use SQLAlchemy ORM with bound parameters (no string concatenation); all user input is parameterized.\n26\t- RLS is set per-transaction by `src/db.session_context` before the first query runs (sets the `app.current_api_key_id` PostgreSQL context variable).\n27\t\n28\t**Row-level security:**\n29\t- Every query includes the authenticated `api_key_id` in the WHERE clause (primary application-layer control).\n30\t- E.g., `WHERE api_key_id = :auth_key AND customer_id = :customer_id` — no unscoped queries.\n31\t- PostgreSQL RLS policy (`USING (api_key_id = current_setting(...))`) is the backstop; the app role has no `BYPASSRLS`.\n32\t- If a query accidentally omits the `api_key_id` filter, RLS blocks it at the database level (defense-in-depth).\n33\t\n34\t**Field projections (minimal surface):**\n35\t- `create_or_replay_event` returns only `{event_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, window_start, idempotent_replay}` — not the full row (which includes `created_at`, `event_time`, `api_key_id`).\n36\t- `read_usage` returns only `{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\n37\t- `api_keys_repo.get_by_key_id` returns the full row (needed by auth for `secret_hash`, `rate_limit_per_sec`, `revoked_at`).\n38\t\n39\t**Constraint enforcement:**\n40\t- `create_or_replay_event` relies on the `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint at the DB level to detect duplicates.\n41\t- If a duplicate key is encountered, PostgreSQL raises an `IntegrityError` (caught by service layer) → the service reads the original row instead.\n42\t- `quantity > 0` and other domain constraints are enforced by CHECK constraints in the schema (verified at insert time).\n43\t\n44\t## Notes\n45\t\n46\t**ON CONFLICT pattern:**\n47\t- The idempotency mechanism uses `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING RETURNING id, ...`.\n48\t- If the unique constraint is violated, the INSERT returns no rows.\n49\t- The service layer checks `if result` — if a row was returned, this request won the insert; if not, a duplicate is detected.\n50\t\n51\t**RLS context setup:**\n52\t- Before any query, `src/db.session_context` sets `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id = :id` in the transaction.\n53\t- This context variable is read by the PostgreSQL RLS policy on every table access.\n54\t- The `SET LOCAL` is per-transaction (automatically cleared at commit), so no context leakage across requests.\n55\t\n56\t**Quota lock-then-read pattern (why it's two statements, not one):**\n57\t- `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` deliberately issues the `FOR UPDATE` lock on `quotas` and the `usage_rollup` read as two separate statements, not a single `LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` query.\n58\t- PostgreSQL's `FOR UPDATE` only forces a fresh re-check (`EvalPlanQual`) of the *locked* row itself when a blocked waiter unblocks after the holder commits — it does **not** force a fresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement, including a joined one.\n59\t- A single combined statement lets a waiter that queued before the holder committed read `usage_rollup` from its own stale pre-wait snapshot — verified empirically during implementation: every concurrent waiter read the same stale total and all got admitted, silently breaking the cap.\n60\t- Issuing the `usage_rollup` read as its own statement *after* the lock is acquired gives it a fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot that does include everything the previous holder just committed — this is what makes `current_total` accurate for every waiter, not just the first uncontended caller (`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n61\t\n62\t**Async pattern:**\n63\t- All functions are async; they use `await session.execute(...)` for queries.\n64\t- They receive an `AsyncSession` that's already connected and in a transaction (setup by `src/db.session_context`).\n65\t- No explicit connection management in the repo; the session is provided by the caller.\n66\t"}]},"uuid":"bc478adb-23ac-4134-9d82-46985eabb3aa","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:11:40.847Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"45222c1f-b25e-4ca9-b6bf-5d5ad5069427","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
