{"parentUuid":"02db7966-3a2b-4269-bb1b-7b82ee7d0fa9","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcrwCSVRPiA5Tb1XENnbW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CSdR5n77YGPABKy2rgsaGV","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\docs\\system_architecture.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4467,"cache_read_input_tokens":90551,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4467,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcrwCRPw9zNW2t7ATcTKd","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"5ee4ac87-f995-445c-99f3-19996e904530","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:13:07.487Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"5ee4ac87-f995-445c-99f3-19996e904530","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CSdR5n77YGPABKy2rgsaGV","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Meterly — system architecture\n2\t\n3\t## Overview\n4\t\n5\tMeterly ingests metered usage events, serves aggregated per-customer/metric\n6\tcounters, and enforces admin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps\n7\t(\"quotas\"). Three authenticated HTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL database, one\n8\tRedis rate-limit store, running as a Docker container on ECS Fargate behind an ALB.\n9\t\n10\t```\n11\tClient --HTTPS+API key--> ALB --> FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\n12\t                                     |-- Tier-1 (IP) / Tier-2 (api_key_id) throttle --> Redis\n13\t                                     |-- bound-parameter SQL, RLS-scoped -------------> RDS PostgreSQL\n14\t                                     |-- DB credential fetch ------------------------> Secrets Manager\n15\t                                     |-- traces/logs/errors -------------------------> CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry\n16\t```\n17\t\n18\t```mermaid\n19\tflowchart LR\n20\t    Client[Client] -->|\"HTTPS + API key\"| ALB[ALB]\n21\t    ALB --> FastAPI[\"FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\"]\n22\t    FastAPI -->|\"Tier-1 IP+route / Tier-2 api_key_id throttle\"| Redis[(Redis)]\n23\t    FastAPI -->|\"require_api_key: cache hit or Argon2id verify\"| AuthDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: api_keys)]\n24\t    FastAPI -->|\"POST /v1/events: insert + quota check + rollup upsert\"| EventsDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: events / usage_rollup / quotas)]\n25\t    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage: read rollup\"| EventsDB\n26\t    FastAPI -->|\"PUT /v1/quotas: upsert cap\"| EventsDB\n27\t    FastAPI -->|\"DB credential fetch\"| Secrets[Secrets Manager]\n28\t    FastAPI -->|\"traces/logs/errors\"| Observability[\"CloudWatch / X-Ray / Sentry\"]\n29\t```\n30\t\n31\t## Request flow — `POST /v1/events`\n32\t\n33\t1. Request-id/trace assigned, security headers queued (`src/logging/middleware.py`, `src/api/middleware.py`).\n34\t2. Tier-1 IP+route throttle (Redis token bucket; fails open on a Redis outage).\n35\t3. `require_api_key` — split-token parse, in-process verification-cache check,\n36\t   falling back to a DB lookup + Argon2id verify on a cache miss\n37\t   (`src/auth/__init__.py`, `src/auth/api_key.py`).\n38\t4. Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`).\n39\t5. Pydantic schema validation (`src/api/schemas/events.py`) — anchored\n40\t   allowlists, `extra='forbid'`.\n41\t6. `events_service.create_event` — one transaction:\n42\t   `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, and only\n43\t   if a row was inserted:\n44\t   - the quota check: `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` locks the caller's\n45\t     quota row for `(customer, metric)` (if one exists) and reads the\n46\t     current-window rollup total fresh; if `R + Q > L` the service raises\n47\t     `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`, `Retry-After` to the next\n48\t     hour boundary), which propagates out of the transaction and rolls back\n49\t     the event insert — no partial write, no rollup increment\n50\t     (`src/services/events_service.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n51\t   - otherwise, `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` the `usage_rollup`\n52\t     counter (`src/repositories/events_repo.py`).\n53\t   A duplicate `idempotency_key` (replay) never reaches the quota check at\n54\t   all — only the winning-insert branch does.\n55\t7. Error-envelope boundary catches anything unhandled and returns the generic\n56\t   `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` shape (`src/api/errors.py`); `AppError`\n57\t   lets a handler attach an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that\n58\t   overrides the default status->code map, so two different 429s\n59\t   (`rate_limited` vs. `quota_exceeded`) stay distinguishable to the caller.\n60\t\n61\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage`\n62\t\n63\tSame auth/throttle/error stack; the service floors `window` to the UTC hour\n64\tand reads a single `usage_rollup` row scoped by the caller's `api_key_id`\n65\t(`src/services/usage_service.py`, `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`). A missing\n66\tbucket returns zeros with 200, never 404.\n67\t\n68\t## Request flow — `PUT /v1/quotas`\n69\t\n70\tAdmin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer, per-metric usage cap.\n71\tAuth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> an `admin`-scope assertion in the\n72\troute's composed dependency (403 `forbidden` for a non-admin key) -> schema\n73\tvalidation (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) -> `upsert_tenant_quota`, a single\n74\t`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ...\n75\tRETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted` that reports create-vs-replace in one\n76\tround-trip (201 create / 200 replace), with a `quota.upsert` audit log\n77\t(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py`,\n78\t`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n79\t\n80\t## Data model\n81\t\n82\t- `api_keys` — the tenant/credential table (migration 0001), extended with a\n83\t  `scope` column (migration 0003: `'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated).\n84\t  `secret_hash` is Argon2id; `key_id` is the public split-token lookup\n85\t  handle. `scope='admin'` is a superset scope — an admin key does everything\n86\t  an ingest key does, plus call `PUT /v1/quotas`; a tenant that wants quotas\n87\t  provisions one admin-scoped key and uses it for both.\n88\t- `events` — append-only ingest log (migration 0001). `UNIQUE (api_key_id,\n89\t  idempotency_key)` is the idempotency guarantee; RLS policy\n90\t  `events_tenant_isolation` is the application-scoping backstop.\n91\t- `usage_rollup` — derived hourly aggregate (migration 0002, expand +\n92\t  backfill from `events`). Composite PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n93\t  window_start)`; RLS policy `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation`.\n94\t- `quotas` — per-tenant, per-customer, per-metric usage caps (migration\n95\t  0003). PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`; `CHECK (limit_per_window >=\n96\t  1)`; RLS policy `quotas_tenant_isolation`. The `POST /v1/events` quota\n97\t  check takes `FOR UPDATE` on this row to serialize concurrent writers for\n98\t  the same `(customer, metric)` — see *Quota enforcement / atomicity* below.\n99\t\n100\t## Quota enforcement / atomicity\n101\t\n102\tStrict enforcement (\"usage can never exceed `L`\") is a check-then-act on a\n103\tshared counter — the classic TOCTOU. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked`\n104\t(`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) makes it race-free with a `SELECT\n105\tlimit_per_window ... FOR UPDATE` on the quota row, run **as a separate\n106\tstatement from the subsequent `usage_rollup` read**, both inside the same\n107\ttransaction as the event insert and rollup increment\n108\t(`src/services/events_service.py`).\n109\t\n110\tThis two-round-trip shape is deliberate, not incidental: PostgreSQL's `FOR\n111\tUPDATE` only guarantees a fresh re-check of the *locked* row itself when a\n112\twaiter unblocks after the lock holder commits — it does **not** force a\n113\tfresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement (e.g. a `LEFT\n114\tJOIN` to `usage_rollup`). A waiter queued before the holder committed would\n115\tevaluate that join against its own pre-wait snapshot and read a stale total,\n116\tsilently letting concurrent writers jointly exceed the cap. Splitting the\n117\tlock-acquire and the rollup-read into two statements gives the second query\n118\tits own fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot (taken *after* the lock is held),\n119\twhich does reflect everything the previous holder just committed. This was\n120\tverified empirically during implementation: a single combined\n121\t`LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` statement let every concurrent waiter read\n122\tthe same stale total and all get admitted; the two-statement version\n123\tcorrectly serializes and caps admission at `L`\n124\t(`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n125\t\n126\tUnlimited customers (no quota row) take no lock at all — the first `SELECT\n127\t... FOR UPDATE` simply matches zero rows, so the common, zero-contention\n128\tpath stays cheap (AC20 measures its added latency under load).\n129\t\n130\t## Auth\n131\t\n132\tSplit-token API keys (`mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`), Argon2id-hashed at rest.\n133\tAn in-process, TTL-bounded verification cache (keyed on the public `key_id`,\n134\tguarded by a constant-time digest comparison) avoids paying the Argon2id cost\n135\ton every request while the durable store stays Argon2id-only. See\n136\t`src/auth/__init__.py` for the full tradeoff writeup and\n137\t`scripts/seed_api_key.py` for the only key-provisioning path (no HTTP\n138\tendpoint in this build's scope; pass `--admin` to provision a `scope='admin'`\n139\tkey for `PUT /v1/quotas`, including the DAST-context admin test key, DAST-3).\n140\t\n141\t## Rate limiting\n142\t\n143\tTwo Redis token-bucket tiers (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`): Tier-1 pre-auth,\n144\tkeyed on IP+route; Tier-2 post-auth, keyed on the authenticated\n145\t`api_key_id`. Both fail open (log a warning, allow the request) on a Redis\n146\tconnection error rather than failing every request — an availability\n147\ttradeoff recorded in `.pipeline/surface-delta.md`.\n148\t\n149\t## Observability\n150\t\n151\tStructured JSON logs (structlog) to stdout -> CloudWatch, with a centralized\n152\tredaction processor (`src/logging/__init__.py`). OTel traces -> ADOT sidecar\n153\t-> X-Ray; Sentry for release-tagged error tracking with a `before_send`\n154\tPII/secret scrubber (`src/observability/`). SLO burn-rate alarms and the\n155\tminimum-three canary alarms are declared in `infra/modules/observability`.\n156\t\n157\t## Infrastructure\n158\t\n159\tTerraform under `infra/`: `modules/{network,compute,data,observability,edge}`\n160\thold the real resources; `envs/{staging,prod}/main.tf` are the two\n161\tself-contained deploy roots (own provider + backend, since Terraform only\n162\tpermits a backend configuration in a root module) that instantiate the same\n163\tmodules at different scale. See each module's file header comments for the\n164\tspecific resources and the security-baseline items they satisfy\n165\t(encryption at rest, private subnets, least-privilege IAM, no `BYPASSRLS`).\n166\t\n167\t## Known deviations / accepted risks\n168\t\n169\tSee `.pipeline/surface-delta.md` for the rate-limit fail-open behavior and the\n170\tOTel/Sentry wiring-at-construction-time change vs. the plan's original\n171\tlifespan-hook placement. See `plan.md`'s \"Open questions\" section for the\n172\taccepted risks around key-revocation latency, `api_key_id`-as-tenant-scope,\n173\tand the Postgres app-role bootstrap's CI-network-reachability prerequisite.\n174\t"}]},"uuid":"96a52d29-ee20-4ca8-b1dc-c41410758dac","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:13:07.531Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5ee4ac87-f995-445c-99f3-19996e904530","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
