{"parentUuid":"2b04c18d-5533-46a2-ba6f-8d72a100468f","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcryAVj4dzBCHsw1wBbCd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01M4CStEw7ZmpSMds9rPHcY7","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\src\\repositories\\README.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":548,"cache_read_input_tokens":231953,"output_tokens":91,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":548},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":91,"cache_read_input_tokens":231953,"cache_creation_input_tokens":548,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":548,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcryAUYNZFP6h332dkAEP","attributionAgent":"implementation","type":"assistant","uuid":"070f05a5-a8fb-4c9a-999f-17416d1c6258","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:37:41.230Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"070f05a5-a8fb-4c9a-999f-17416d1c6258","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"42022266-80ed-4b1b-af25-460921b78a21","agentId":"ab73956eb6c77cae9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M4CStEw7ZmpSMds9rPHcY7","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# src/repositories/\n2\t\n3\t## Purpose\n4\t\n5\tData access layer: SQL queries with parameterization, row-level scoping (by authenticated `api_key_id`), and minimal-field projections. All database I/O is encapsulated here.\n6\t\n7\t## Modules\n8\t\n9\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| `events_repo.py` | `create_or_replay_event(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO NOTHING (idempotency). Also `upsert_rollup()` (called only on insert success). |\n12\t| `usage_repo.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). |\n13\t| `api_keys_repo.py` | `find_active_key_by_key_id(key_id)` — SELECT from `api_keys` by public `key_id` (used by auth cache miss); returns the full row including `scope`. `create_api_key(..., scope=\"ingest\")` — the only key-provisioning path. |\n14\t| `quotas_repo.py` | `upsert_quota(...)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted`, reporting create-vs-replace in one round-trip. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(...)` — the atomic check-then-decide: locks the quota row (`FOR UPDATE`), then reads the current-window rollup total as a **separate, fresh** statement (see *Notes* below for why). Returns `None` when no quota exists (unlimited, no lock taken). |\n15\t\n16\t## Relationships\n17\t\n18\t**Public surface:**\n19\t- Imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, quota_service}` to execute queries.\n20\t- `api_keys_repo` is also imported by `src/auth.api_key` (credential lookup on cache miss).\n21\t- `quotas_repo` is imported by both `quota_service` (the upsert) and `events_service` (the read-and-decide).\n22\t\n23\t**Dependencies:**\n24\t- All functions are async; they receive an `AsyncSession` from the service layer (obtained via `src/db.session_context`).\n25\t- Queries use SQLAlchemy ORM with bound parameters (no string concatenation); all user input is parameterized.\n26\t- RLS is set per-transaction by `src/db.session_context` before the first query runs (sets the `app.current_api_key_id` PostgreSQL context variable).\n27\t\n28\t**Row-level security:**\n29\t- Every query includes the authenticated `api_key_id` in the WHERE clause (primary application-layer control).\n30\t- E.g., `WHERE api_key_id = :auth_key AND customer_id = :customer_id` — no unscoped queries.\n31\t- PostgreSQL RLS policy (`USING (api_key_id = current_setting(...))`) is the backstop; the app role has no `BYPASSRLS`.\n32\t- If a query accidentally omits the `api_key_id` filter, RLS blocks it at the database level (defense-in-depth).\n33\t\n34\t**Field projections (minimal surface):**\n35\t- `create_or_replay_event` returns only `{event_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, window_start, idempotent_replay}` — not the full row (which includes `created_at`, `event_time`, `api_key_id`).\n36\t- `read_usage` returns only `{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\n37\t- `api_keys_repo.get_by_key_id` returns the full row (needed by auth for `secret_hash`, `rate_limit_per_sec`, `revoked_at`).\n38\t\n39\t**Constraint enforcement:**\n40\t- `create_or_replay_event` relies on the `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint at the DB level to detect duplicates.\n41\t- If a duplicate key is encountered, PostgreSQL raises an `IntegrityError` (caught by service layer) → the service reads the original row instead.\n42\t- `quantity > 0` and other domain constraints are enforced by CHECK constraints in the schema (verified at insert time).\n43\t\n44\t## Notes\n45\t\n46\t**ON CONFLICT pattern:**\n47\t- The idempotency mechanism uses `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING RETURNING id, ...`.\n48\t- If the unique constraint is violated, the INSERT returns no rows.\n49\t- The service layer checks `if result` — if a row was returned, this request won the insert; if not, a duplicate is detected.\n50\t\n51\t**RLS context setup:**\n52\t- Before any query, `src/db.session_context` sets `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id = :id` in the transaction.\n53\t- This context variable is read by the PostgreSQL RLS policy on every table access.\n54\t- The `SET LOCAL` is per-transaction (automatically cleared at commit), so no context leakage across requests.\n55\t\n56\t**Quota lock-then-read pattern (why it's two statements, not one):**\n57\t- `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` deliberately issues the `FOR UPDATE` lock on `quotas` and the `usage_rollup` read as two separate statements, not a single `LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` query.\n58\t- PostgreSQL's `FOR UPDATE` only forces a fresh re-check (`EvalPlanQual`) of the *locked* row itself when a blocked waiter unblocks after the holder commits — it does **not** force a fresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement, including a joined one.\n59\t- A single combined statement lets a waiter that queued before the holder committed read `usage_rollup` from its own stale pre-wait snapshot — verified empirically during implementation: every concurrent waiter read the same stale total and all got admitted, silently breaking the cap.\n60\t- Issuing the `usage_rollup` read as its own statement *after* the lock is acquired gives it a fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot that does include everything the previous holder just committed — this is what makes `current_total` accurate for every waiter, not just the first uncontended caller (`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n61\t\n62\t**Async pattern:**\n63\t- All functions are async; they use `await session.execute(...)` for queries.\n64\t- They receive an `AsyncSession` that's already connected and in a transaction (setup by `src/db.session_context`).\n65\t- No explicit connection management in the repo; the session is provided by the caller.\n66\t"}]},"uuid":"ff0f3ad4-9a83-4f9d-b876-f775a7d241bf","timestamp":"2026-07-09T18:37:41.259Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"070f05a5-a8fb-4c9a-999f-17416d1c6258","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
